  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although \"Protagonists of War\" published by Leuven University Press in 2021 has not garnered academic citations or online mentions to date, its commercial presence on platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads indicates a potential audience engaging with this work outside of traditional academic channels.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Protagonists of War,\" a scholarly work published by Leuven University Press in 2021, presents an exploration of the dynamics surrounding war and its actors. Despite the lack of formal academic citations or significant public discourse as reflected in platforms like Wikipedia, Twitter, and Reddit, the work demonstrates a notable commercial linkage, suggesting ongoing interest from a broader readership, particularly through its listings on Amazon and Goodreads.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While many academic publications rely on citations as key indicators of influence, \"Protagonists of War\" showcases a unique engagement through commercial platforms. The presence of the title on well-known bookselling sites entices potential readers and signifies its relevance to those interested in wartime narratives, thus positioning the work within the sphere of public interest.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The inferred roles attributed to this work suggest a strong commitment to maintaining a visible presence in public discourse, evidenced by a high score in \"Active Public Discourse.\" This indicates an alignment with the societal conversations surrounding warfare narratives, even if these discussions have not yet manifested in online metrics or academic citations.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, while \"Protagonists of War\" may not yet hold a prominent place within academic discourse reflected in traditional metrics, its commercial visibility and potential impact suggest it resonates with readers and offer a foundation that could foster further engagement in both scholarly and public spheres in the future.</p>",
